      <div purpose="report-section">
        <h2>Key findings</h2>
        <ul purpose="report-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Only a quarter say their devices are fully enrolled and upgraded.</strong>
            <p>Only 23% say that all or nearly all of their devices are enrolled in their MDM, and 25% have all or nearly all of their devices running the last OS. The remainder only have a fraction of their devices enrolled or upgraded.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>They struggle the most with miscellaneous operating systems and iOS.</strong>
            <p>When it comes to managing operating systems, they struggle the most to manage miscellaneous platforms (36%), iOS (29%), and Android (26%). Additionally, Windows (40%) and Linux (27%) are often used but not currently included in their MDM.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The top best practice is having a bring-your-own-device policy.</strong>
            <p>When it comes to best practices that make their MDM approach effective, respondents say having a documented BYOD policy in place (32%) is key. They also find success measuring point-in-time compliance across all devices (31%) and reporting how quickly vulnerable software is patched (30%). </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Compliance verification is their top challenge.</strong>
            <p>The biggest challenges they face daily with their MDM is being able to verify compliance across devices (22.9%), getting all their devices enrolled (21%), and maintaining accurate visibility across all their devices (21%).</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>A complicated MDM was their top deployment challenge.</strong>
            <p>While deploying and implementing their MDM, respondents found it too complicated to configure and understand (36.1%). They also encountered confusing or limited documentation (34%), difficulties with SSO integration (33%), and that it was hard to get support (33%).</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Only about half are finding their MDM effective.</strong>
            <p>47% have sufficient visibility into enrolled devices, 49% effectively maintain secure laptops and servers, 52% respond to incidents in a timely manner, 55% have enough visibility to investigate in real time, and 49% effectively enforce compliance and security posture — but the remainder aren’t finding these in their MDM.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Multi-factor authentication is their top priority for 2022.</strong>
            <p>Over the next year, respondents want to focus on device security such as multi-factor authentication (MFA) at login (18.1%), implementing zero-touch enrollment (14.2%), and patching third-party applications and packages (13.2%).</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
